{"accepted":[{"assertion":"Formal-Conjectures statement: Erdos1055.erdos_1055 https://google-deepmind.github.io/formal-conjectures/theorem/?name=Erdos1055.erdos_1055.","id":"vf_64d5cb88d4fd0c2c","trust":"signed","type":"theoretical"},{"assertion":"Erdős Problem #1055: declared status 'open'. Formalized: yes. A prime $p$ is in class $1$ if the only prime divisors of $p+1$ are $2$ or $3$. In general, a prime $p$ is in class $r$ if every prime factor of $p+1$ is in some class $\\leq r-1$, with equality for at least one prime factor.\n\nAre there infinitely many primes in each class? If $p_r$ is the least prime in class $r$, then how does $p_r^{1/r}$ behave? Prize: no. OEIS: A005113. Tags: number theory, primes.","id":"vf_7ca640a9b7b59415","trust":"signed","type":"theoretical"}],"accepted_activity":false,"activity":[],"activity_types":[],"attempt_count":0,"banked_attempt_count":0,"commits":[],"dependency_impact":"none","detail_url":"problems/1055.json","draft_proposals":[],"edges":[{"evidence":"Problem identity derived from the accepted finding's pinned source anchor.","inferred":true,"relation":"describes","source":"vf_64d5cb88d4fd0c2c","source_root":"sha256:a4d62c3b7a2ca0a02a1bf4ce1b4ad0ffb06b6f2f61ff9f5b58ed8ee07d8b2bf1","target":"erdos:1055","trust":"signed"},{"evidence":"Materialized typed link between accepted findings.","inferred":true,"relation":"synthesized_from","source":"vf_64d5cb88d4fd0c2c","source_root":"sha256:a4d62c3b7a2ca0a02a1bf4ce1b4ad0ffb06b6f2f61ff9f5b58ed8ee07d8b2bf1","target":"vf_7ca640a9b7b59415","trust":"signed"},{"evidence":"Problem identity derived from the accepted finding's pinned source anchor.","inferred":true,"relation":"describes","source":"vf_7ca640a9b7b59415","source_root":"sha256:a4d62c3b7a2ca0a02a1bf4ce1b4ad0ffb06b6f2f61ff9f5b58ed8ee07d8b2bf1","target":"erdos:1055","trust":"signed"}],"external_references":[],"formal_conjectures_activity":null,"frontier_id":"vfr_0a25edabc16db143","frontier_root":"sha256:a4d62c3b7a2ca0a02a1bf4ce1b4ad0ff